{
  "texts": [
    "Thus, ■ i X satisfies refinability.Now let us prove the implication from 1 to 2.",
    "First, suppose that R-rule does not hold, so we have x ′ ⊑ x and x ′ R i y ′ ≬ z, but for all y with xR i y, we havey ⊥ z.",
    "Let V = {v ∈ S | v ⊥ z}, so x ∈ ■ i V.One can check that V satisfies persistence and refinability (see Fact 6.16), soV ∈ RO(S, ⊑).",
    "Since y ′ ≬ z, y ′ ̸ ∈ V, which with x ′ R i y ′ implies x ′ ̸ ∈ ■ i V. But then since x ′ ⊑ x, x ∈ ■ i V, and x ′ ̸ ∈ ■ i V, ■ i V does not satisfy persistence, so ■ i V ̸ ∈ RO(S, ⊑).",
    "But then since V ∈ RO(S, ⊑), RO(S, ⊑) is not closed under ■ i.Second, suppose that R⇒win does not hold, so we have xR i y and ∃y′ ⊑ y ∀x ′ ⊑ x ∃x ′′ ⊑ x ′ ∀y ′′: x ′′ R i y ′′ implies y ′′ ⊥ y ′."
  ]
}